<section class="container section-stack">
  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <span class="eyebrow">What owners usually care about</span>
      <h2>
        Less disruption, clearer communication, and work that is easier to
        maintain later
      </h2>
      <p>
        In commercial spaces, the appearance and organization of the work often
        matter almost as much as the electrical correction itself. Better
        labeling, cleaner routing, realistic scheduling, and practical handoff
        reduce future confusion for staff, tenants, and service providers.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="quote-grid">
      <div class="quote-card">
        <p>
          Active properties need clean work areas and scope clarity, not
          avoidable surprises.
        </p>
        <cite>Occupied spaces</cite>
      </div>
      <div class="quote-card">
        <p>
          Tenant improvements work better when the electrical plan is settled
          early and documented clearly.
        </p>
        <cite>Fit-outs &amp; reconfigurations</cite>
      </div>
      <div class="quote-card">
        <p>
          Well-labeled equipment saves time every time a future service call
          happens.
        </p>
        <cite>Panels &amp; controls</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <span class="eyebrow">Typical commercial flow</span>
  <div class="process-grid">
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>1</strong>
      <h3>Review the operating context</h3>
      <p>
        Understand how the property is used, what must stay active, and what
        disruption windows are realistic.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>2</strong>
      <h3>Diagnose or scope the work</h3>
      <p>
        Identify the electrical issue or define the improvement so the right
        work is priced and scheduled.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>3</strong>
      <h3>Execute with control</h3>
      <p>
        Complete the work neatly, coordinate around occupancy, and keep the job
        understandable to decision-makers.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>4</strong>
      <h3>Close out clearly</h3>
      <p>
        Label, explain, and hand off the finished work so future maintenance and
        tenant support are easier.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

